(43, 3, 28, 39, 4, 4, 5, 'I am not the Christ, but that I am sent before him', 'Connection Between John and Malachi', 'This connection highlights the role of a forerunner. John the Baptist identifies himself as one sent before Christ, paralleling Malachi''s prophecy of Elijah coming before the Lord.', 'prophecy', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 29, 23, 54, 5, 5, 'bridegroom', 'Bride and Bridegroom Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between the bride and the bridegroom, symbolizing a deep connection. In John, the bridegroom''s joy reflects the intimate bond, while Isaiah portrays the Maker as the husband, highlighting divine union.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 29, 28, 2, 19, 19, 'bridegroom', 'Bride and Bridegroom Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between the bride and bridegroom, symbolizing a covenantal bond. John 3:29 reflects joy in the bridegroom''s presence, while Hosea 2:19 speaks of a betrothal, highlighting commitment and love.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 29, 40, 9, 15, 15, 'bridegroom', 'Bridegroom Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the bridegroom, highlighting joy in his presence and the sorrow in his absence. The concept of the bridegroom serves as a central theme in both texts, linking them through the imagery of celebration and mourning.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 29, 49, 5, 25, 27, 'he that hath the bride is the bridegroom', 'Bride and Bridegroom Imagery', 'This connection highlights the imagery of the bride and bridegroom, where John 3:29 refers to Christ as the bridegroom and Ephesians 5:25-27 describes the church as the bride. Both passages emphasize the relationship between Christ and the church, portraying it as a sacred union.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 29, 26, 16, 8, 8, 'bridegroom', 'Bride and Bridegroom Imagery', 'This connection highlights the imagery of covenant love and relationship. In John, the bridegroom represents a joyful union, while Ezekiel describes a covenant relationship marked by love and commitment.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 29, 66, 19, 7, 9, 'he that hath the bride is the bridegroom', 'Marriage Imagery in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of the bride and bridegroom, with John 3:29 referencing the bridegroom and Revelation 19:7-9 discussing the marriage of the Lamb. Both passages emphasize joy and celebration associated with this union.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 29, 66, 21, 9, 9, 'the bridegroom', 'Bride and Bridegroom Connection', 'This connection highlights the imagery of the bride and bridegroom in both passages. John 3:29 refers to the bridegroom, while Revelation 21:9 explicitly mentions the bride, the Lambâ€™s wife, emphasizing the relationship between Christ and His followers.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 30, 51, 1, 18, 18, 'He must increase', 'Preeminence and Decrease', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of Christ''s supremacy. John 3:30 suggests that Christ must increase, while Colossians 1:18 states that He is to have preeminence in all things.', 'theme', 0.5589999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 30, 19, 72, 17, 19, 'He must increase', 'Increase and Endurance of Name', 'This connection highlights the theme of enduring greatness. John 3:30 emphasizes the necessity of Christ''s increase, while Psalms 72:17-19 speaks of the everlasting nature of His name and glory.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 30, 58, 3, 2, 6, 'He must increase, but I must decrease.', 'Faithfulness and Authority Comparison', 'This connection highlights the contrast between Moses and Christ, where Christ''s authority and glory surpass that of Moses. The idea of decreasing personal status in favor of a greater authority is reflected in both passages.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 30, 23, 9, 7, 7, 'He must increase', 'Increase of His Government', 'This connection highlights the theme of increase in both passages. John 3:30 speaks of Christ''s increase, while Isaiah 9:7 refers to the increase of His government and peace.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 30, 66, 11, 15, 15, 'He must increase', 'Increase and Reign Connection', 'This connection highlights the transition of authority from human to divine. In John 3:30, the emphasis on Christ''s increase parallels the declaration in Revelation 11:15 of Christ''s eternal reign over the kingdoms.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 30, 46, 3, 5, 5, 'I must decrease', 'Ministry and Humility Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of humility in ministry. John 3:30 emphasizes the need for self-decrease in favor of Christ''s increase, while 1 Corinthians 3:5 reflects on the role of ministers as servants, indicating that their significance lies in leading others to faith rather than in personal glory.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 30, 44, 13, 36, 37, 'He must increase, but I must decrease.', 'Increase and Decrease in Service', 'This connection highlights the theme of serving one''s generation and the transition of roles. John the Baptist''s call for decrease reflects David''s earthly service, while Christ''s resurrection signifies his increase and eternal role.', 'theme', 0.356, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 31, 40, 28, 18, 18, 'he that cometh from above is above all', 'Authority from Above', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority, as both passages emphasize the superiority of Jesus'' power. John 3:31 states that Jesus ''is above all,'' while Matthew 28:18 affirms that ''All power is given unto me in heaven and in earth.''', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 31, 43, 8, 23, 23, 'he that cometh from above', 'Connection of Origin and Nature', 'This connection highlights the contrast between those who are ''from above'' and those who are ''of this world.'' Both passages emphasize the distinction between heavenly and earthly origins, reinforcing the idea of Jesus'' divine nature.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 31, 43, 6, 33, 33, 'he that cometh from heaven', 'Connection of Heavenly Origin', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of coming from heaven. John 3:31 speaks of one who ''cometh from above,'' while John 6:33 refers to ''he which cometh down from heaven.'' This connection highlights the significance of divine origin in relation to life.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 31, 45, 9, 5, 5, 'is above all', 'Divine Authority of Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the supremacy of Christ, highlighting His divine origin and authority. John 3:31 states that He ''is above all,'' while Romans 9:5 affirms that Christ ''is over all.''', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 31, 62, 4, 5, 5, 'he that cometh from above is above all', 'Connection of Worldly Perspectives', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between those who are from above and those who are of the world. The earthly nature of speakers in John 3:31 parallels the worldly perspective of those in 1 John 4:5.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 31, 50, 2, 9, 11, 'he that cometh from above is above all', 'Exaltation of Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the superiority of Christ, with John 3:31 stating that he ''that cometh from above is above all,'' and Philippians 2:9 declaring that God ''hath highly exalted him.'' This connection highlights the theme of Christ''s divine authority and exaltation.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 31, 66, 19, 16, 16, 'he that cometh from above is above all', 'Heavenly Authority Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority from heaven. Both passages emphasize the supremacy of the one who comes from above, establishing Him as the ultimate ruler.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 32, 43, 3, 11, 11, NULL, 'Testimony and Witness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of testimony and the rejection of that testimony. They highlight the speaker''s assertion of knowledge and experience that is not received by the audience.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
